Ah, OK, OK.

00:23:56.215 --> 00:23:56.940
[LAUGHS]

00:23:56.940 --> 00:23:57.720
APRAJITA JAIN: It
shows that ads work.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:23:59.664
It becomes reality
for some people.

00:23:59.664 --> 00:24:00.830
SANJEEV KAPOOR: That's true.

00:24:00.830 --> 00:24:01.580
That's true, yeah.

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:02.746
APRAJITA JAIN: Great, great.

00:24:02.746 --> 00:24:04.610
Thank you for sharing
that, the real story.

00:24:04.610 --> 00:24:05.484
SANJEEV KAPOOR: Yeah.

00:24:05.484 --> 00:24:07.840
APRAJITA JAIN: In general,
there's this image about,

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:10.900
as you said, that chefs didn't
used to be as highly regarded,

00:24:10.900 --> 00:24:11.920
until you came around.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.100
And people started, ha
ha, [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:24:15.100 --> 00:24:17.440
So how has that changed
over the years in India?

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:18.970
And with the new
crop coming up, how

00:24:18.970 --> 00:24:21.580
do you feel people are being
encouraged to take that up

00:24:21.580 --> 00:24:22.777
as a serious career option?

00:24:22.777 --> 00:24:24.610
SANJEEV KAPOOR: Well,
fortunately, the times

00:24:24.610 --> 00:24:26.750
have changed.

00:24:26.750 --> 00:24:30.340
So when my first
job in a hotel, I

00:24:30.340 --> 00:24:35.080
was actually asked by
the GM of the hotel,

00:24:35.080 --> 00:24:39.490
I'd gone to meet a tour
leader of a group checking

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:40.690
into our hotel.

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:41.560
So I'd gone to meet.

00:24:41.560 --> 00:24:44.050
And our reception was
in the lobby area.

00:24:44.050 --> 00:24:46.690
So I had gone from
kitchen there.

00:24:46.690 --> 00:24:49.150
And the GM of the hotel
was standing there.

00:24:49.150 --> 00:24:51.360
And he actually said, yes, Chef?

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:54.440
I said, sir, I have come
to meet the tour leader

00:24:54.440 --> 00:24:57.110
to ask what they want to eat.

00:24:57.110 --> 00:24:59.370
No, but you can't
be in the lobby.

00:24:59.370 --> 00:25:02.300
So it's not second-hand
information.

00:25:02.300 --> 00:25:03.080
It's first-hand.

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:05.770
But I was actually asked
by the GM of a hotel

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:11.060
that chefs are not allowed to be
in the lobby of the hotel, OK?

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:14.650
So that was sad.

00:25:14.650 --> 00:25:15.870
That was not something.

00:25:15.870 --> 00:25:17.180
But I rebelled.

00:25:17.180 --> 00:25:21.530
I said, OK, now whatever I
couldn't do, I would change.

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:26.280
I've worked really
hard to do that.

00:25:26.280 --> 00:25:27.540
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:29.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:31.960
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:34.610
So I often say this
in India, especially,

00:25:34.610 --> 00:25:37.717
that [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:25:37.717 --> 00:25:39.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:39.650 --> 00:25:41.685
So people now don't
want to be a chef.

00:25:41.685 --> 00:25:44.550
They often say, sir, how
can we be a celebrity chef?

00:25:44.550 --> 00:25:45.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:45.050 --> 00:25:47.549
SANJEEV KAPOOR: I said, there's
nothing as a celebrity chef.

00:25:47.549 --> 00:25:49.970
It's the world that you would
do should be celebrated.

00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:53.990
Yeah, it's not-- you
cannot become, so--

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:55.550
but no, it's a change.

00:25:55.550 --> 00:26:00.600
I'm glad that
change has happened.

00:26:00.600 --> 00:26:03.710
It's not happened in a
rush, I can tell you.

00:26:03.710 --> 00:26:08.090
It's been a very long
time it has taken.

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:13.410
And even now, it's
not that easy.

00:26:13.410 --> 00:26:15.230
I can tell you.

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:23.637
So two weeks ago, so I
was awarded the Padma Shri

00:26:23.637 --> 00:26:24.720
by the president of India.

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:32.990
And so I decided that I would
wear chef's uniform for that.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:36.620
But the invitation that was
there, it said, national dress.

00:26:39.690 --> 00:26:40.930
OK?

00:26:40.930 --> 00:26:44.970
So now what do you do?

00:26:44.970 --> 00:26:46.906
What do you wear?

00:26:46.906 --> 00:26:48.780
Because it's the
invitation, and that's what,

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:49.613
and it's a protocol.

00:26:49.613 --> 00:26:52.400
You have to follow that.

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:55.450
So I asked them,
and they said, yeah,

00:26:55.450 --> 00:26:59.350
if it says national dress,
then it's national dress.

00:26:59.350 --> 00:27:02.750
So I said, OK.

00:27:02.750 --> 00:27:05.140
What happens when these
awards and all are

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:11.020
given to uniformed
services people that's

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:13.660
in military and Army, Navy?

00:27:13.660 --> 00:27:18.010
No, no, no, they get
decorated on their uniform.

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:22.150
So I said, OK, I'm going
to wear my chef's uniform,

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:25.334
and [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:27:25.334 --> 00:27:27.250
APRAJITA JAIN:
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] [CHUCKLES]

00:27:27.250 --> 00:27:30.880
SANJEEV KAPOOR:
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:34.877
So it takes time, but
yeah, I will get there.

00:27:34.877 --> 00:27:35.960
APRAJITA JAIN: Absolutely.

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:36.835
SANJEEV KAPOOR: Yeah.

00:27:36.835 --> 00:27:38.337
APRAJITA JAIN: And
from not knowing

00:27:38.337 --> 00:27:40.670
what to do in your career to
becoming Padma Shri Sanjeev

00:27:40.670 --> 00:27:41.390
Kapoor.

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:43.220
So tell us a little
bit about what

00:27:43.220 --> 00:27:46.130
are the qualities in a chef that
you think are really important.

00:27:46.130 --> 00:27:49.030
I mean, it sounds like it's not
something that is born, right?

00:27:49.030 --> 00:27:50.280
You can develop that talent.

00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:51.760
But is it the right ingredients?

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:54.300
Is it the right cookware?

00:27:54.300 --> 00:27:55.300
Is it the right mindset?

00:27:55.300 --> 00:27:57.722
Like what, for you,
makes a perfect chef?

00:27:57.722 --> 00:28:00.180
SANJEEV KAPOOR: Somebody who's
involved with Akshaya Patra.

00:28:00.180 --> 00:28:01.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:04.590
[APPLAUSE]

00:28:05.570 --> 00:28:08.160
SANJEEV KAPOOR: No, the reason
that I'm here is Akshaya Patra.

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:10.885
Lots of people who
have come in now,

00:28:10.885 --> 00:28:13.850
we have to raise lots of
money for Akshaya Patra.

00:28:13.850 --> 00:28:15.410
And we talked about it.

00:28:15.410 --> 00:28:21.940
It only takes $15 per
year to feed one child.

00:28:21.940 --> 00:28:28.360
And the 1.6 million kids a
day, a staggering number.

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:31.280
And as Sandeep
yesterday mentioned,

00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:37.660
it's only we are feeding 1.5%
of the total need that is there

00:28:37.660 --> 00:28:38.590
in India.

00:28:38.590 --> 00:28:40.780
So imagine what they needed.

00:28:40.780 --> 00:28:44.300
So one needs a lot
of money to grow.

00:28:44.300 --> 00:28:47.460
So please do your bit.

00:28:47.460 --> 00:28:48.310
OK.

00:28:48.310 --> 00:28:59.440
Coming back to your question,
I think, in any profession,

00:28:59.440 --> 00:29:00.850
the ingredients are same.

00:29:00.850 --> 00:29:05.170
It's not-- they don't
work any differently,

00:29:05.170 --> 00:29:08.350
so whether it's knowledge,
whether it's hard work.

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:11.380
But what I have realized,
the biggest thing is--

00:29:14.770 --> 00:29:17.380
which we normally don't
quantify, we don't say,

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:20.250
we don't factor that in--

00:29:20.250 --> 00:29:23.810
is the value system.

00:29:23.810 --> 00:29:29.710
All the things that we learned
from our parents, family,

00:29:29.710 --> 00:29:32.030
It's all the good things that--

00:29:32.030 --> 00:29:34.760
all the boring things.

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:39.920
That's something which
you'd say, oh, what is this?

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:47.450
I think that is probably one
of the most important things

00:29:47.450 --> 00:29:48.800
in any success.

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:49.600
APRAJITA JAIN:
Especially In cooking.

00:29:49.600 --> 00:29:51.016
I think it's a
generational thing.

00:29:51.016 --> 00:29:52.480
I learned cooking from my mom.

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:54.320
But [INAUDIBLE],,
there's certain things.

00:29:54.320 --> 00:29:56.630
I stand right next to
her when she's cooking.

00:29:56.630 --> 00:29:58.040
I write down
everything she does.

00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:59.680
I follow her instructions.

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:01.782
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:30:01.782 --> 00:30:03.740
SANJEEV KAPOOR: Well,
she's just a better cook.

00:30:03.740 --> 00:30:04.100
Face it.

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:04.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:04.350 --> 00:30:06.310
APRAJITA JAIN: Yeah,
I'm completely on board.

00:30:06.310 --> 00:30:07.780
Yes, she is.

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:08.350
Yes, she is.

00:30:08.350 --> 00:30:10.625
Her rasgullas always turn
out spongier than mine.

00:30:10.625 --> 00:30:11.750
There's something about it.

00:30:11.750 --> 00:30:13.280
But you're right,
there is something

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:16.684
that is not quantifiable that
just comes with, I guess,

00:30:16.684 --> 00:30:17.350
experience, or--

00:30:17.350 --> 00:30:19.460
SANJEEV KAPOOR: No
these are experience.

00:30:19.460 --> 00:30:22.947
And also, we talk
about energies, right?

00:30:22.947 --> 00:30:23.780
APRAJITA JAIN: Yeah.

00:30:23.780 --> 00:30:26.660
SANJEEV KAPOOR: So same
is the case in cooking.

00:30:26.660 --> 00:30:29.220
So you cook with
positive energy.

00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:33.830
It'll come out--
it's a known thing.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:36.750
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH] mothers.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:40.520
So she exactly knows
who she's cooking for.

00:30:40.520 --> 00:30:43.780
You can never get that
in restaurant food.

00:30:43.780 --> 00:30:45.410
Never, you would get it.

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:53.300
But on especially
younger people,

00:30:53.300 --> 00:30:59.820
people who want to become
chefs, so there are two things.

00:30:59.820 --> 00:31:04.130
One is the skills, because
it's a job of skill, right?

00:31:04.130 --> 00:31:07.610
So they have to
perfect the skills.

00:31:07.610 --> 00:31:14.720
And that's around a
big layer of knowledge.

00:31:14.720 --> 00:31:18.560
So get great skills,
have great knowledge.

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:22.140
And then wrap that around
with a great value system.

00:31:22.140 --> 00:31:24.590
So if you get these
three things right--

00:31:24.590 --> 00:31:26.610
skill, knowledge,
and value system--

00:31:26.610 --> 00:31:28.125
you can be a great chef, easy.

00:31:28.125 --> 00:31:29.000
APRAJITA JAIN: Great.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:30.050
Thank you.

00:31:30.050 --> 00:31:32.150
So you have done so many
things in your career,

00:31:32.150 --> 00:31:33.900
in addition to just
being an amazing chef.

00:31:33.900 --> 00:31:35.691
And I had to make a
list and write it down,

00:31:35.691 --> 00:31:37.490
because I would forget
all of those things.

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:40.580
Some of them are you
own over 75 restaurants,

00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:42.980
starting with The Yellow
Chilli, I believe.

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:45.130
You have your own
cookbook series.

00:31:45.130 --> 00:31:47.630
You own a ready-to-cook
meal line.

00:31:47.630 --> 00:31:49.760
You have your own
food TV network.

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:53.030
You have hosted many TV shows.

00:31:53.030 --> 00:31:56.110
You are a brand ambassador for
kitchen brands and for Ariel,

00:31:56.110 --> 00:31:57.620
as I learned.

00:31:57.620 --> 00:32:01.790
You introduced a culinary art
course at Symbiosis in Pune.

00:32:01.790 --> 00:32:04.340
You have cooked for the
Indian prime minister.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:06.320
You have designed
an airline menu.

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:08.810
And you have been approached
by the Indian railways

00:32:08.810 --> 00:32:11.180
to design their menu as well.

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:12.957
How can you wear all
these hats and still

00:32:12.957 --> 00:32:14.040
do justice to all of them?

